e":"1237–Overleden","about 1309":"circa 1309","1237":"1237","1378":"1378","about 1317":"circa 1317","1330":"1330","1264":"1264","1250":"1250","about 1264":"circa 1264","Abt 1292":"circa 1292","1309":"1309","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1264–about 1317":"about 1264–about 1317","1264–1317":"1264–1317","1250–1330":"1250–1330","1309–1378":"1309–1378","1237–Male":"1237–Deceased","about 1309":"about 1309","1237":"1237","1378":"1378","about 1317":"about 1317","1330":"1330","1264":"1264","1250":"1250","about 1264":"about 1264","Abt 1292":"about 1292","1309":"1309","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gawthorpe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from any of several places called Gawthorpe in Yorks and Lancs, including Gawthorpe in Osset, Gawthorpe in Lepton, a lost Gawthorpe Hall in Harewood (WR Yorks), Gowthorpe in Bishop Wilton (ER Yorks), and Gawthorpe Hall in Hagergham Eaves (Lancs), all earlier recorded as  <i>Goukthorpe</i>. See   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gawthrope","meanings":["English:  see  Gawthorpe  ."]},{"name":"Gawthrop","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): habitational name from any of several places in Yorkshire and Lancashire called Gawthorpe or Gowthorpe, all of which are named from Old Norse <i>gaukr</i> ‘cuckoo’ + <i>thorp</i> ‘enclosure’."]},{"name":"Gawthorp","meanings":["English:  see  Gawthorpe  ."]},{"name":"Gowthorpe","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Gowthorpe in Blacktoft (ER Yorks). Some of the following early bearers may alternatively belong with (2).","2  English:  see  Gawthorpe  ."]},{"name":"Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames","meanings":["English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Wat</i>, a pet form of  <i>Walter</i>, and Middle English  <i>maugh</i>,  <i>mough</i> ‘kinsman by marriage, brother-in-law, son-in-law’.  See  Mowe   (1), and compare Robert Waltersmaghe, 1305 in   Black  . In origin it was mainly a Lancs surname, that spread eastwards and southwards in post-medieval times.   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes that in 1634 Joshua Watmough of London granted land to a man from Bradford (WR Yorks), and was described as ‘a younger son of Hugh Watmough late of Bury’ (Lancs)."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Gawthorpe was born about 1264 as the daughter of John of Gawthorpe. She married William Gascoigne about 1292, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1317, at the age of 55."},"et":{"about 1264–about 1317":"umbes 1264–umbes 1317","1